<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<methodology slug="websocket-design">
  <metadata>
    <tier>solo</tier>
    <group>dev</group>
    <domain>software-developer</domain>
    <summary>Full-duplex persistent connections. Authenticate on handshake before accept(), implement heartbeats below LB timeout, reconnect with exponential backoff + jitter.</summary>
    <tags>
      <tag>websocket</tag>
      <tag>real-time</tag>
      <tag>networking</tag>
      <tag>server-push</tag>
      <tag>scalability</tag>
    </tags>
    <difficulty>intermediate</difficulty>
    <created>2026-04-26</created>
  </metadata>
  <content>
    <title>WebSocket Design</title>
    <summary>WebSocket provides full-duplex, persistent connections between clients and servers. Core rule: authenticate on the upgrade handshake before accepting the connection, implement heartbeats below the load-balancer idle timeout, and reconnect with exponential backoff plus jitter on the client side.</summary>
    <why>
      <p>Polling for frequently changing data wastes requests and adds latency. WebSockets enable server-push with sub-100ms delivery. Without heartbeats, stale connections consume file descriptors indefinitely. Without reconnect backoff, a server restart triggers a reconnect storm that DDoSes your own service.</p>
    </why>
    <when-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>Real-time UI features: chat, presence indicators, live cursors, notification feeds</item>
        <item>Server-pushed updates where polling burns requests (price tickers, game state, dashboards)</item>
        <item>Bidirectional protocols (collaborative editing, low-latency RPC) where SSE alone is insufficient</item>
        <item>Frontends needing one persistent connection multiplexed across many topics per user</item>
      </list>
    </when-to-use>
    <when-not-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>One-way server-to-client streams — use Server-Sent Events; simpler, works through more proxies</item>
        <item>Request/response-style RPC — use HTTP/gRPC; WebSockets add framing overhead and connection state</item>
        <item>Behind aggressive corporate proxies that strip WebSocket upgrades — fall back to long-polling</item>
        <item>Serverless platforms without WS support — use AWS API Gateway WebSockets or Cloudflare Durable Objects</item>
      </list>
    </when-not-to-use>
    <section name="authentication">
      <rule>
        <statement>Authenticate on the WebSocket upgrade handshake before calling `accept()`. Never accept anonymous connections and authorize later.</statement>
        <rationale>Once `accept()` is called, the connection is established and consumes a file descriptor. Validating auth before acceptance allows the HTTP layer to return 401/403 with no WS overhead.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <rule>
        <statement>Validate the `Origin` header server-side against an allowlist. Same-origin is not enforced for WebSocket upgrades by browsers.</statement>
        <rationale>WebSocket upgrade requests bypass the browser's same-origin CSRF protections. An attacker can craft a page that initiates a WS connection to your server from any origin.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>
    <section name="connection-lifecycle">
      <rule>
        <statement>On disconnect, clean up all channel subscriptions atomically. Stale user IDs in channel subscription maps cause broadcasts to dead connections and memory leaks.</statement>
        <rationale>A subscription map that retains disconnected users wastes memory and causes errors on send attempts. The disconnect handler must iterate all user channels and remove memberships.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <rule>
        <statement>Check connection state before sending (`ws.client_state == CONNECTED`). Sending to a closed WebSocket raises an exception and must be caught.</statement>
        <rationale>Disconnect and send can race: the connection drops between the state check and the actual send. Always wrap send in a try/except and disconnect on error.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>
    <section name="message-envelope">
      <rule>
        <statement>Use a versioned typed message envelope: `{ v, type, channel, data, id }`. The `type` field drives routing; `channel` scopes delivery.</statement>
        <rationale>Untyped messages require downstream parsing to determine handling. A versioned envelope allows protocol upgrades without breaking existing clients — clients ignore unknown `v` values gracefully.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <example type="good" title="Typed message envelope in Python">
        <code lang="python"><![CDATA[
from enum import Enum
from dataclasses import dataclass
from typing import Optional
import json

class MessageType(str, Enum):
    PING = "ping"
    PONG = "pong"
    SUBSCRIBE = "subscribe"
    UNSUBSCRIBE = "unsubscribe"
    MESSAGE = "message"
    ERROR = "error"
    ACK = "ack"

@dataclass
class WSMessage:
    type: MessageType
    channel: Optional[str] = None
    data: Optional[dict] = None
    id: Optional[str] = None

    def to_json(self) -> str:
        return json.dumps({k: v for k, v in self.__dict__.items() if v is not None})
        ]]></code>
      </example>
    </section>
    <section name="multi-instance-architecture">
      <rule>
        <statement>For multi-instance deployments, use Redis (or NATS) pub/sub fan-out. Each server instance subscribes to channel patterns and delivers only to its locally connected users.</statement>
        <rationale>Without a message bus, a broadcast sent to instance A never reaches users connected to instance B. Redis pub/sub propagates the message to all instances; each delivers only to its own subscribers.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <rule>
        <statement>Skip self-publish: when a message originates locally, deliver it directly without publishing to Redis first, or filter by instance ID when consuming.</statement>
        <rationale>Publishing to Redis and then consuming the same message from Redis produces duplicate delivery for locally subscribed users. Either skip Redis for local delivery or stamp messages with the originating instance ID and skip on re-receipt.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>
    <section name="sticky-sessions">
      <rule>
        <statement>Configure the load balancer for sticky sessions (IP hash or cookie affinity) when using in-memory subscription maps.</statement>
        <rationale>Without sticky sessions, two requests from the same user can arrive at different instances. The second instance has no record of the WebSocket connection opened on the first instance.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <example type="good" title="Distributed connection manager with Redis fan-out">
        <code lang="python"><![CDATA[
# Distributed connection manager: fan-out via Redis
async def broadcast_to_channel(self, channel: str, message: WSMessage):
    """Publish to Redis so all instances deliver to their local subscribers."""
    await self.redis.publish(
        f"ws:channel:{channel}",
        message.to_json()
    )

async def _listen_to_redis(self):
    """Consume messages from other instances and deliver locally."""
    await self.pubsub.psubscribe("ws:channel:*")
    async for msg in self.pubsub.listen():
        if msg["type"] != "pmessage":
            continue
        channel = msg["channel"].decode().replace("ws:channel:", "")
        data = json.loads(msg["data"])
        # Deliver only to users connected on THIS instance
        await self._local_broadcast(channel, WSMessage(**data))
        ]]></code>
      </example>
    </section>
    <section name="reconnect-strategy">
      <rule>
        <statement>Reconnect with exponential backoff and random jitter. Never reconnect immediately on close.</statement>
        <rationale>Immediate reconnect after a server restart causes a reconnect storm from all clients simultaneously, DDoSing the server. Exponential backoff spreads reconnects over time; jitter prevents synchronized retry waves.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <rule>
        <statement>Buffer outgoing messages during disconnect and flush on reconnect. Assign idempotency keys to messages that must not be duplicated.</statement>
        <rationale>Messages sent during a transient disconnect are lost if not queued. Flushing the queue on reconnect ensures delivery without requiring the caller to retry manually.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>
    <section name="heartbeat">
      <rule>
        <statement>Set the ping interval below the load-balancer idle timeout. Close the connection if no pong is received within 2 × ping interval.</statement>
        <rationale>AWS ALB default idle timeout is 60s. A 30s ping interval keeps the connection alive. Without heartbeats, stale connections consume file descriptors without the server knowing they are dead.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>
    <section name="backoff-formula">
      <example type="good" title="Exponential backoff with jitter in TypeScript">
        <code lang="typescript"><![CDATA[
private handleReconnect() {
  if (this.reconnectAttempts >= this.maxReconnectAttempts) {
    console.error('Max reconnection attempts reached');
    return;
  }
  // Exponential backoff with jitter
  const base = this.reconnectDelay * Math.pow(2, this.reconnectAttempts);
  const jitter = Math.random() * 1000;
  const delay = base + jitter;
  this.reconnectAttempts++;
  setTimeout(() => this.connect().catch(console.error), delay);
}
        ]]></code>
      </example>
    </section>
    <section name="connection-anti-patterns">
      <antipattern>
        <description>No heartbeat: connections sit idle and the server never detects stale connections.</description>
        <reason>Stale connections accumulate and consume file descriptors. On Linux, the default `nofile` limit is 1024. 10k idle connections exhaust the limit and block new connections.</reason>
      </antipattern>
      <antipattern>
        <description>No per-connection or per-user limit on concurrent connections.</description>
        <reason>A single user or bot can open thousands of connections, exhausting server resources and starving legitimate users.</reason>
      </antipattern>
      <antipattern>
        <description>No authentication on the upgrade handshake — anonymous connections accepted, authorization checked after the first message.</description>
        <reason>Unauthenticated connections consume resources before rejection. If auth is checked after the first message, an attacker can open thousands of connections without sending any data.</reason>
      </antipattern>
    </section>
    <section name="message-handling-anti-patterns">
      <antipattern>
        <description>Blocking or CPU-intensive operations inside async message handlers.</description>
        <reason>Async WebSocket handlers run on the event loop. A blocking call (file read, CPU hash, synchronous DB) stalls all other WebSocket connections on the same worker until it completes.</reason>
      </antipattern>
      <antipattern>
        <description>Sending large payloads (tens of KB or more) directly in WebSocket messages.</description>
        <reason>Large messages block the send buffer, introduce latency for other subscribers, and can cause memory pressure. Use HTTP for large payloads; send only a reference ID over WebSocket.</reason>
      </antipattern>
      <antipattern>
        <description>Subscription state keyed by socket object rather than user ID, causing authorization to leak across reconnects.</description>
        <reason>On reconnect, a new socket is created. If subscriptions are keyed by socket, old subscriptions linger. If keyed by user ID without revoking old sockets, a user might receive messages intended for a different session.</reason>
      </antipattern>
    </section>
    <section name="agentic-workflow">
      <p>Drive WebSocket work in three layers: (1) protocol design (message envelope: `type`, `channel`, `data`, `id`, `ts` — versioned), (2) server connection-manager (connect/disconnect/subscribe/broadcast), (3) client with reconnect + queue + heartbeat. Use a subagent to enforce the message-envelope schema with TypeScript/Pydantic models on both sides, regenerated from a single source. Always implement an auth handshake on `connect` before subscribing — never accept anonymous upgrades and authorize later.</p>
      <list>
        <item>ws-protocol-architect (Sonnet) — defines message envelope, channel naming, versioning.</item>
        <item>ws-server-implementer (Sonnet) — writes the connection manager, channel manager, distributed pub/sub adapter.</item>
        <item>ws-client-implementer (Sonnet) — writes the client with reconnect, queue, heartbeat, subscribe/unsubscribe lifecycle.</item>
        <item>ws-loadtester (Sonnet) — runs `k6` or `artillery` ws scenarios, measures p95 latency at N connections.</item>
        <item>ws-security-reviewer (Sonnet) — checks auth handshake, origin validation, rate limits, message-size cap.</item>
      </list>
    </section>
    <section name="best-practices">
      <list>
        <item>Authenticate on the upgrade handshake, not after — pass a short-lived JWT in `Sec-WebSocket-Protocol` (more proxy-friendly than query strings) or in a cookie set by a recent HTTP login.</item>
        <item>Validate `Origin` server-side against an allowlist; same-origin is not enforced for WebSockets.</item>
        <item>Use a typed message envelope versioned via `v` field (`{ v: 1, type, channel, ... }`) so clients/server can negotiate.</item>
        <item>Heartbeats: set ping interval below load-balancer idle timeout; close connection if no pong in 2× interval.</item>
        <item>Implement per-connection bounded queues; drop or close on overflow rather than buffering unbounded.</item>
        <item>Cap message size (e.g., 64 KB) at the framework level (FastAPI, Starlette, ws lib option).</item>
        <item>For multi-instance deployment, use Redis/NATS pub/sub fan-out and trace cross-instance latency.</item>
        <item>Reconnect with exponential backoff + jitter on the client; never reconnect immediately on close.</item>
        <item>Buffer outgoing messages on the client during disconnect; flush on reconnect (with idempotency keys).</item>
        <item>Keep recent history (last N messages) on the server, sent on subscribe/reconnect to fill gaps.</item>
        <item>Apply rate limits per connection (msg/sec) and per user across connections.</item>
        <item>Log every connect/disconnect with reason code + duration; alarms on disconnect-rate spikes.</item>
      </list>
    </section>
    <section name="agent-gotchas">
      <list>
        <item>The README's example connection manager has a subtle bug: `disconnect` while inside `connect()`'s try block races; agents replicate this pattern. Require a redesign that doesn't call `disconnect` during `accept`.</item>
        <item>Agents leave `print`/`logging.error` instead of structured logging — every WS error needs `connection_id`, `user_id`, `channel`, `code`.</item>
        <item>Forgotten cleanup: subscribers map keeps stale `user_id`s after disconnect — verify membership cleanup with a goroutine/task count test.</item>
        <item>Agents enable broadcast across instances by adding Redis pub/sub but forget to skip self-publish — leads to message dupes.</item>
        <item>Reconnect storms after deploy: agents copy "reconnect immediately" code; require backoff + jitter with `Math.random()`.</item>
        <item>Forgetting `ctx.client_state == CONNECTED` check before send — raises on a closed socket.</item>
        <item>Agents broadcast unbounded objects (`data: &lt;huge json&gt;`) — enforce envelope size cap server-side.</item>
        <item>Subscriptions leaking across user sessions: agents key state by socket but reuse user_id across reconnects without revoking old subscriptions.</item>
        <item>Authorization on subscribe is forgotten — agents allow any client to subscribe to any channel including admin channels.</item>
        <item>Human-in-loop checkpoint: any new channel/message type that crosses tenancy boundaries (cross-user broadcast, admin events) needs human review of the auth path.</item>
      </list>
    </section>
    <templates>
      <template path="templates/connection-manager.py" purpose="FastAPI ConnectionManager with channel subscriptions and broadcast"/>
      <template path="templates/ws-client.ts" purpose="TypeScript WebSocketClient with reconnect, queue, and heartbeat"/>
    </templates>
